post_text:
Winners of the Hollidaysburg Planetarium LOGO Contest.

Over the past several months, as just one of her many ongoing projects, Alysia Watt, Art Teacher at Hollidaysburg High School, has been instructing her students in the making of a logo. Six entire classes participated in the project and the 5 top winners were given cash prizes provided by Fred Marschak, Planetarium Volunteer. The new planetarium logo was created by Noah Schenk, a Junior at Hollidaysburg High. There were many logos submissions to choose from and the final decision was difficult. Congratulations to Noah and all the students who participated.

LAST FAMILY CHRISTMAS SHOWS at Hollidaysburg Planetarium

Reservations for a NEW SET of Christmas Shows at the Hollidaysburg Planetarium are NOW OPEN by going to astroprof.com

There are 3 new showings each Thursday evening, Friday evening, and Saturday mid-day on 12/19-20-21. Sign up for BOTH!!

‘The Star of Bethlehem’ is the NEW show at the Hollidaysburg Planetarium this season. The show takes you back to the little town of Bethlehem of long ago, in the endeavor to investigate the question “What was the “Star” that guided the Wise Men.

The other Christmas show is ‘Cosmic Christmas’. This show was seen by over 900 people last season and is a musical light show. Wonderful for the entire family – suggested ages 5-6 and up. This is a medley of a dozen songs by a variety of artists from Maria Carey and Destiny’s Child to Paul McCartney and Bing Crosby. You are invited to sing along with any of these favorites!

To make your confirmed reservations, go to astroprof.com

post_text:
Sign-up for our NEW Planetarium show for the entire family is now open at astroprof.com!!
Join Coyote, a confused but witty character, as he explores common misconceptions about our Earth, Moon, and Sun system. Learn about lunar phases, solar eclipses, lunar eclipses, and more. Coyote's antics are sure to entertain young audiences.
This planetarium show explores the relationship between Earth, Moon and Sun with the help of Coyote, an amusing character adapted from Native American oral traditions. Coyote has many misconceptions about our home planet and its most familiar neighbors. His confusion about the universe makes viewers think about how Earth, Moon and Sun work together as a system and learn to distinguish between myths and science.

post_text:
A NEW Planetarium Show at Hollidaysburg Planetarium!!
The 6 PM show will be the ongoing fulldome show about comets and meteorites striking the Earth called ‘Incoming’. This is a visually striking program that the planetarium will only be showing over the next few months.
The 7 PM show will be the LIVE show call ‘Understanding the Zodiac Constellations’ presented by Fred Marschak. This show explains the origins of the Zodiac Constellations, why they are not aligned with current astrology, and how our sky changes them over longer periods of time.
At 8 PM will premier the newest show about the history of the telescope called ‘Two Small Pieces of Glass: The Amazing Telescope’ as a fulldome movie. This program also includes some current evening sky and some actual examples of the various types of telescopes.
For further information about each show and to make verified reservations, please go to astroprof.com for details. You may also call the planetarium at 693-3975 and leave a message. Calls are returned as time permits.

post_text: Another step toward installation!! Last week we had the removal of the old planetarium - don't worry Rick Imler had it saved for a future exhibit!! Spitz came and removed the instrument, all the wiring, and the elevator as well as the old dome lighting system in preparation of the installation this June. Now, the district will paint the dome, cover the hole, and prep for the electrical hookups needed before the actual installation. The planetarium room is officially a construction zone!!

Spitz came and removed the instrument, all the wiring, and the elevator as well as the old dome lighting system in preparation of the installation this June. Now, the district will paint the dome, cover the hole, and prep for the electrical hookups needed before the actual installation. The planetarium room is officially a construction zone!!

"The Hollidaysburg Area School District will receive sealed bids for the Senior High School Digital 4K Planetarium System until 2:00 p.m. on Wednesday, October 4, 2017, at 405 Clark Street, Hollidaysburg, PA 16648. Specifications may be obtained by downloading the forms at http://tigerwires.com/domain/5 or at the Administration Office, 405 Clark Street, Hollidaysburg, PA 16648. The Board reserves the right to accept or reject any or all bids."

While we are not finished with the "Save the Planetarium" fundraising, this is an important milestone we wanted to share with our loyal followers!

post_text: Tomorrow, starting at 1:30pm, at the Patton Public Library!
shared_text:
Patton Public Library
August 19, 2017 at 11:26 AM ·

The Library will have a Sunspotter Telescope available on Monday starting around 1:30 PM.
It will be set up during the eclipse.
Lanika Ruzhitskaya from Saint Francis gave a presentation Wed evening during Cosmic Treats about the upcoming eclipse and she left the sunspotter here for the library to use on Monday.
The Sunspotter is a refracting telescope. It has a large objective lens and a smaller eyepiece lens. The objective lens magnifies an image (the sun), and the eyepiece lens focuses it.
Stop in on Monday afternoon and view the eclipse through a Sunspotter.

post_text: Science Cafe: Cosmic Cocktails, July 6th, at 7 PM at the Allegheny Creamery and Crepes. A retired NASA rocket engineer who worked for Apollo missions will give a talk about the past and the future space explorations (including trips to the Moon, of course). As always, 20% of all sales and 50% of the special cocktail, The Dark Side of the Moon, the restaurant will donate to the Hollidaysburg Planetarium!
shared_text:
Science Cafe: Cosmic Cocktails
June 25, 2017 at 10:15 PM ·

The next Science Cafe: Cosmic Cocktails event will happen on Thursday, July 6th at 7:00 pm at Allegheny Crepes & Creamery in Hollidaysburg, Pa.
Join us for an evening science talk about the Earth’s natural satellite Luna (or as you might call it, the Moon). Find out about the history of the race to the Moon between two powerful countries on Earth, goals set by NASA, Apollo missions, great discoveries, and about work of NASA engineers behind the curtains.
Our special guest speaker, F. Don Freeburn, a retired NASA Apollo and space shuttle rocket engineer, will take us on a tour through the history of NASA and he will introduce to us future plans of space and the Moon explorations.
Please come early and order lots of food and drinks since 20% of patrons' bills the ENTIRE day is donated to the restoration efforts of the Hollidaysburg Area High School Planetarium. A special drink during the event will have 50% of its cost donated to the planetarium.
Please come for great food and drinks, a free science/history lesson and help a great cause!

Allegheny Crepes will donate 20% for the entire day on Thursday, 6/1, to the Save the Planetarium Fund!! The restaurant is open from 7 AM to 8 PM.
The next Cosmic Cocktails event will also occur on Thursday, June 1st at Allegheny Creamery & Crepes. Fred Marschak, Hollidaysburg's first planetarium director, will give a talk on "The Great American Eclipse of 2017". This total solar eclipse on Monday, August 21, 2017 will be the first total solar eclipse to transverse the USA in 99 years! Discover how this type of eclipse happens, why there is not an eclipse every new Moon, and what time of year we could have eclipses.
Come early and order a lot of food and drinks since 20% of all patron bills are donated to the Hollidaysburg Area High School Planetarium fund. A special drink will have 50% of its proceeds donated to the planetarium.
The talk begins at 7:00 pm upstairs.

Join your friends and neighbors for a great meal on Thursday, 3/30, from 3 PM-10 PM at Texas Roadhouse where the ‘Save the Hollidaysburg Planetarium Fund’ will get 20% of the business for that day!!
Our NEW supply of great T-shirts will be available besides homemade baked goods, 3D Saturns/Solar Systems, and some old planetarium pics to bring back memories.

You MUST do ONE of the following for the Planetarium to get the 20%:
* take a flyer - available on the Hollidaysburg Planetarium Facebook page.
OR
* Show your server a pic of the flyer from your phone
OR
* Simply tell your server you are there for the 20% donation to the Planetarium Fund

Please HELP!!

post_text: Silent Auction Item: “Planetarium Party” includes a 1.5 hour party at the Neil Armstrong Planetarium in Altoona. The party will have a sky show of your choice, night sky study with star charts, and scavenger hunt for up to 50 people. Party organizers have a ½ hour set up and ½ hour clean up time included in the prize. Also included are model rocket kits, popcorn and 2 dozen custom cupcakes! (Please note the party must happen between September and May on a Monday, Tuesday, or Wednesday evening due to classes and community sky shows.) Thank you Neil Armstrong Planetarium!!

post_text:
Silent Auction Item #12: EUGENE & CAROLYN SHOEMAKER FRAMED AUTOGRAPHS

Gene Shoemaker is often referred to as the ‘Father of Planetary Geology’. He proved that Impacting Cratering was a very important planetary process. He trained most of the Apollo astronauts who later went to the Moon.

Gene’s wife Carolyn graduated from CalTech with a degree in Chemical Engineering. She worked with Gene as a field assistant as they raised their family.
text:
Silent Auction Item #12: EUGENE & CAROLYN SHOEMAKER FRAMED AUTOGRAPHS

Gene Shoemaker is often referred to as the ‘Father of Planetary Geology’. He proved that Impacting Cratering was a very important planetary process. He trained most of the Apollo astronauts who later went to the Moon.

Gene’s wife Carolyn graduated from CalTech with a degree in Chemical Engineering. She worked with Gene as a field assistant as they raised their family.

post_text:
Silent Auction Item #11: Personally collected autographs from a Symposium called ‘Saturn and the Mind of Man’ at CalTech in 1980.

Includes framed autographed booklet, plus an unsigned booklet, and ticket. Also included is an autographed copy of a Saturn Educator’s Conference Program by William Pickering. Bill was former Director of JPL for many years and is famous for directing the launch of the USA’s first satellite.

Silent Auction #10: Sally Ride's autographed book 'Voyager - An Adventure to the Edge of the Solar System.'

Sally was an American physicist and astronaut. Born in Los Angeles, she joined NASA in 1978 and became the first American woman in space in 1983. She became a great inspiration to young women dreaming of jobs in the sciences and space technologies.

post_text: A great day today - the Tiger Pride Day! This morning, the planetarium team was busy spreading the word about upcoming Great American Eclipse (exactly one year and one day from today). Fred Marschak brought eclipse glasses with special filter (remember never loook directly at the sun; your sunglasses are not good protection) and a big telescope so everybody could look at the sun safely! And, of course, huge chunks of meteorites were right hete on display! Nathan Stull was making light sabers with kids and offered people lemonade (which was much needed today!). Eddie Zovinka helped fundraising money for the restoration of the planetarium, he was selling raffle tickets for cool Star Wars memorabilia. More to come! The day is not over yet :)

post_text:
Here comes another great 'Professor Fred' (Fred Marschak) program!

Professor Fred, Professor Emeritus of Earth & Planetary Sciences, Santa Barbara City College & former astronomy teacher at Hollidaysburg High School, will be leading this hour of Cosmic Treats this Thursday June 23 at 6 PM at the Hollidaysburg Area Public Library.

Everyone attending will make a simple AstroFinder or Astrolabe and learn to use it just as people did 2000 years ago. With this instrument they could tell the Earth was round, they could determine the size of the Earth & how far they were from the equator (their latitude), and they could mark the daily positions of the planets on a star chart.

All the materials will be provided free for each person, and hands-on instructions as to how to use your new astrolabe will be included.

Of course, there will also be snacks!

This free program is a partnership with Dr. Lanika Ruzhitskaya, Director of Science Outreach, Saint Francis University. All are welcome; no signup is needed, children must be accompanied by an adult.
